Figure 3 is a plot of formula_200 vs. formula_201 for various values of the Pitzer factor formula_202 as given by this equation. The vertical axis is logarithmic in order to show the behavior at pressures closer to zero, where differences among the various substances (indicated by varying values of formula_202) are more pronounced.

Figure 4 is another plot of the same equation showing formula_201 as a function of formula_202 for various values of formula_200. It includes data from 51 substances, including the vdW fluid, over the range formula_207. This plot shows that the vdW fluid (formula_208) is a member of the class of real fluids; indeed, the vdW fluid can quantitatively approximate the behavior of the liquid metals cesium (formula_209) and mercury (formula_210), which share similar values of formula_202. However, in general it can describe the behavior of fluids of various formula_202 only qualitatively.

== Joule–Thomson coefficient ==

The Joule–Thomson coefficient, formula_213, is of practical importance because the two end states of a throttling process (formula_214) lie on a constant enthalpy curve. Although ideal gases, for which formula_215, do not change temperature in such a process, real gases do, and it is important in applications to know whether they heat up or cool down.

This coefficient can be found in terms of the previously derived formula_123 and formula_125 as
